pressure and time is rival sons
sophomore LP and it's pretty good it's
10 songs in 30 minutes of some
straight-up blues rock and hard rock
they've gone back and listen to their
Sabbath's they've listened to their Hoos
they've listened to their Led Zeppelin's
and from the guitar playing on this
album and some of the vocal phrasing I
could only guess that these guys
definitely have some blues records in
their collections too along with some
Creedence Clearwater Revival and maybe
some animals because this song young
love definitely sounds like a little bit
of Eric Burdon is in the vocals along
with the bass and drum combo but on the
song white noise things change up a lot
these guys take the album into a
surprisingly psychedelic direction with
fuzz Dow guitars and just an
overwhelming amount of sound and it kind
of reminds me of something I could hear
like the who playing to end out a live
set with Pete Townsend just smashing his
guitar all over the stage but on a
majority of these tracks the musical
group that comes to mind the most as an
influence has got to be Led Zeppelin
which kind of becomes a
thing at a bad thing the guitarist here
is no Jimmy Page and the singer is no
Robert Plant and I never really come
away from any of these tracks and man
that guitar player has chops or the
freezing and the singing is really
ambitious and emotional but maybe these
guys save their really flashy playing
for their live shows as a unit these
guys really shine it's not like you're
gonna listen to this just from the
guitars or just for the vocals you're
gonna listen to this because these guys
are a tight band that writes some really
lean catchy and great songs and maybe
that could be a good thing for some
people because often Zeppelin have been
critiqued as being a little too
indulgent for their own good you know
and if you're looking for something of a
hard rock style that's more
straightforward more to the point maybe
this is for you
there are some really standout tracks on
this LP for me I love pressure and time
the title the guitar riff and the drum
be in that song just make me want to
like go downtown and just start
strutting in that electric piano that
pops in over the chorus great and I like
that these guys can put slower and
softer tracks on this LP and keep them
as interesting as the more upbeat songs
but I think the combination of hearing
this stuff before and hearing it done
better is holding me back a little bit
it doesn't ruin the album for me it's
nice to hear a modern sound on this kind
of stuff there wasn't a single song that
I hated
just some impressed me more than others
